  "prompt": "What is the Romeo and Juliet law?",
  "response": "The \"Romeo and Juliet\" law is a term used to describe laws that aim to reduce or eliminate the severity of charges and penalties for statutory rape or sexual activity between two minors or between a minor and a young adult who are close in age. These laws are named after the famous Shakespearean play, which portrays the tragic love story of two young lovers.\n\nThe purpose of Romeo and Juliet laws is to prevent young people from being charged with serious sexual offenses when they engage in consensual sexual activity with someone close to their own age. These laws recognize that young people may engage in sexual activity with peers without either party being exploited or harmed.\n\nRomeo and Juliet laws vary by jurisdiction, and the specific age differences and legal provisions can differ from one place to another. In general, these laws provide legal protection for consensual sexual relationships between minors or between a minor and a slightly older partner, as long as the age difference falls within a specified range.\n\nFor example, a Romeo and Juliet law might state that a 17-year-old who has consensual sex with a 15-year-old will not be charged with statutory rape, even though the age of consent might be 18. However, if the older partner were significantly older, such as 25, they could still face charges.\n\nIt is important to understand the specific Romeo and Juliet laws in your jurisdiction, as they can impact legal outcomes significantly. If you have questions about the law in your area, it is advisable to consult with a legal professional.",
